On Escalation Ticket # 00414105 the new comment has been added: Ionatan-Beneamin Oltean:

Hello, 
The different behaviour is due to different server setups.
The cloud server has allowlisted XML files and the client is not scanning those. Please beware the even though the file sent is and office file (.docx) the actual structure of such a document is a .zip archive that contains .xml files inside it.

As you can see in the eppclient.log file from the cloud logs, xml files are allowlisted, and in the second screenshot during the text scan the file is ignored because of this setting. 




Having the same allowlists on the server will result in identical behaviour for the clients.
Please note that the allowlists are not set per policy, but from Denylists and Allowlists -> Allowlists -> Mime Type -> XML / DTD

On Escalation Ticket # 00419481 the new comment has been added: Cristian-Alexandru Halmajan:

Hi Eduard, @WaitingOnEngineer,

I hope you are well.

The acceptance criteria for the improvements in 5.9.5.0 is:
"The Brazil PIIs should be detected correctly. If the CAP policy has Brazil ID and driver's license checked and an ID is sent over an exit point it should be detected as ID not as driver's license and vice versa.

Test samples:
85619875150 - driver's license
856.198.751-50 - driver's license
57.376.355-6 - ID"


The item description:
"Based on partner feedback, please analyze input provided to customer, verify, and improve detection of Brazilian PII's.

tools on the internet to make the test and probability of a real document easier.

https://www.4devs.com.br/validador_cpf
In this online tool the developer can validate whether the CPF (Tax ID in Brazil) document is real.
It is composed of 11 numbers, but 12345678912 is not a valid number.



12345678912
12345678913
12345678914
12345678915
12345678916

I used this false sequence of 5 sets of numbers of 11 characters each, and the product still identifies this as Brazilian ID, which triggers a series of false positives in various actions when DPI is active in a deeper form.

Here in Brazil we also have the "CNH" or driver's rack, it is also composed of 11 numbers, but with a different verification logic from the "CPF" (Personal Tax ID). Your validation can also be identified online through the link below.
https://www.4devs.com.br/validador_cnh

Of the types of PII we have in Brazil, these 2 are the fundamental ones.
the CPF is used for "personal financial identification".
The CNH is used for "driver identification" but is used for personal identification (registration as a photo).

There are others that have greater complexities, but these two types are the most urgent.



Verify if at least we can ignore false positive digits chain like 12345678...."

Could you please confirm what test build you sent over to the client? Which agent version?
Thank you,
Cristi

There are 2 cases where the EPP Client is blocking files based on metadata even if metadata scanning is not enabled:
1. When the users attach a random file which does not contain brazil PIIs, but it gets detected and blocked as if it contained brazil PIIs (logs related to this: epp_logs_metadata_piis (1).zip)
2. When the users are sending a google meet invitation, the EPP Client is reporting some file uploads even if the customer is not attaching anything to the e-mail. This issue was not reproducing with the EPP Client v6.2.2.1006. (logs related to this: epplogs (6).zip and the video)

Let me know if this helps

Thank you,
